\f3\i Goma
\f0\i0  Ritual):
\f1\b0  The ritualized burning of negative energy provides a powerful, non-cognitive path for emotional detox and release, effectively bypassing the cultural and social stigma surrounding open discussion of anxiety and mental hardship.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 II. The Japanese Youth Psychological Landscape: Understanding the Target Audience\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 To develop relevant self-help content, a precise understanding of the current psychological burdens carried by Japanese youth is essential. These hardships are rooted in cultural and structural dynamics, which necessitate non-traditional spiritual solutions.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 2.1. The Crisis of Internal Worth: Conformity, 
\f3\i Honne/Tatemae
\f0\i0 , and the Pressure to "Save Face"\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Japanese youth face intense, often unrelenting academic pressure, beginning at an early age and continuing through the highly competitive educational system. This environment places immense pressure on students to perform well in exams, leading to chronic stress and widespread low self-confidence.\
Underlying the academic stress is a profound social pressure to conform to societal norms and expectations. The cultural emphasis on "saving face" and avoiding the burden of others means that failure or emotional distress must often be concealed. The pervasive stigma surrounding mental health further complicates this, as emotional or neurological disorders are often perceived as a "sign of weakness" or a lack of willpower. This structural repression means that cognitive techniques requiring open discussion of personal and emotional matters are often ineffective or inaccessible.\
The result of this conditional value system\'97where worth is tied to external adherence and achievement\'97is widespread dissatisfaction. Only 62% of Japanese 15-year-olds report a high life satisfaction score. Even when external accomplishments are achieved, young people often feel profoundly unhappy, indicating that the source of the problem is internal and related to an insecure sense of self. The psychological requirement is not merely acceptance, but a radical philosophical underpinning that declares self-worth to be unconditional and inherent, providing resilience against external judgment.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 2.2. The Digital Burnout: Overload, Isolation, and Fragmented Focus\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Contemporary Japanese youth are deeply immersed in the digital sphere. Surveys indicate that young Japanese spend an average of over five hours a day online on weekdays, with some individuals reporting usage clocking up to eight hours daily. This level of digital saturation contributes significantly to feelings of overwhelm, particularly as this demographic consumes more news than any other content type.\
The negative impacts of this digital immersion are often indirect but profound. While digital use itself has small direct effects on loneliness, the increase in screen time significantly reduces offline, face-to-face communication time, indirectly influencing loneliness to a large degree. Furthermore, social media platforms, driven by public (one-to-many) online communication, have become environments where cyberbullying and harmful content thrive, exacerbating feelings of alienation and increasing vulnerability to self-destructive thoughts.\
In response to this mental fragmentation, Japanese self-help trends show a clear preference for practices rooted in the concept of a \'91Way\'92 (
\f2\i Michi
\f1\i0  or 
\f2\i D\uc0\u333 
\f1\i0 ), focusing on practical self-cultivation that integrates the mind and body. This highlights a growing desire for holistic methods that repair the dualistic rift often created by overly cognitive or digitally-mediated existence. Practices that actively demand and cultivate 
\f2\i presence
\f1\i0  in the body are necessary antidotes to digital diffusion.\
